s submitted to the court in May 1817, the case is not settled until December 1819. In March 1817 Jefferson’s friend James Monroe begins his first term as president. During the summer Jefferson learns of the death of two friends, Madame de Staël Holstein and Pierre Samuel Du Pont de Nemours. Late in the summer he visits Natural Bridge with two of his granddaughters. Jefferson continues to purchase books from Europe with the assistance of George Ticknor, and Stephen Cathalan helps him restock his wine cellar and pantry. Even though Jefferson answers his voluminous correspondence selectively, he still chafes under the burden.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvArchives. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAbigail Adams.  aAbolitionism.  aAeneid.  aAgriculture.  aAlbert Gallatin.  aAlexander von Humboldt.  aAmerican Colonization Society.  aAmerican National Biography.  aAmerican Philosophical Society.  aAnnals (Tacitus).  aBalthasar Bekker.  aBenedict Arnold.  aBenjamin Hallowell Carew.  aBenjamin Henry Latrobe.  aBenjamin Robins.  aBushrod Washington.  aCalculation.  aCollector of the Port of New York.  aConsideration.  aConstantius II.  aContinental Army.  aCorrespondent.  aDartmouth College.  aDavid Hosack.  aDeWitt Clinton.  aDeclaration of independence.  aDeed.  aDemocritus.  aDormitory.  aEdward Coles.  aElkanah Watson.  aFraud.  aGeorge Ticknor.  aHartford Convention.  aHarvard University.  aHis Family.  aHistorical society.  aHoly Alliance.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIndulgence.  aInstitution.  aInvoice.  aIsaac Chauncey.  aJ. (newspaper).  aJohn Randolph of Roanoke.  aJohn Trumbull.  aJohn Vanderlyn.  aJoseph Reed (politician).  aJuvena